cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.COMM, cs.SY, cs.MM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with the use of improper Gaussian signaling (IGS) in full-duplex relaying (FDR) with non-negligible residual self-interference (RSI) under Nakagami-m fading. Information theory concepts such as outage probability and ergodic rate are used to evaluate the system performance. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper discusses the use of full-duplex relaying (FDR) in wireless networks and proposes a method to alleviate residual self-interference (RSI) using improper Gaussian signaling (IGS). 
3. cs.COMM (Computer Communications and Networks): The paper deals with the performance evaluation of a communication system using full-duplex relaying (FDR) and improper Gaussian signaling (IGS) over Nakagami-m fading channels. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a method to optimize the relay signal parameters based on channel statistics to improve the system performance. This involves the use of control theory concepts. 
5. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper discusses the throughput performance of the proposed system and compares it with other relaying schemes, which is relevant to multimedia applications.
